'''Alexander François Selligue''' (1784-1845) was a French engineer. In 1832, he together with David Blum patented an application of [[shale oil]] for direct illumination. In 1838, he patented "the employment of mineral oils for lighting". His process of distilling [[bituminous shale]]s ([[oil shale]]) was first described in the ''Journal des Connaissances Usuelles'' in 1834.<ref name=silliman> {{Cite journal | last= Silliman | first= B | title= Review of Dr. Antisell's Work on Photogenic or Hydrocarbon-Oils from Coal | journal= The American Journal of Science and Arts | publisher = New Haven Editors | volume = 29 | issue= 2 | pages = 118–119 |date=May 1860 | url= https://books.google.com/?id=KsEEAAAAYAAJ&pg=RA1-PA119&dq=Selligue+process | accessdate=2009-06-05}} </ref> This process for the oil shale retorting was first used in [[Autun]], France, in 1838.<ref name=iom> {{cite journal | title = Studies of the Scottish oil shale industry. Vol.1 History of the industry, working conditions, and mineralogy of Scottish and Green River formation shales. Final report on US Department of Energy |author1=Louw, S.J. |author2=Addison, J. | editor = Seaton, A. | publisher = [[Institute of Occupational Medicine]] | url = http://www.instoccmed.com/pubs/IOM_TM8502.pdf | page = 35 | year = 1985 | format = PDF | id = DE-ACO2 – 82ER60036 | accessdate = 2009-06-05}} </ref> This is considered the start of the modern [[oil shale industry]].
