{{Infobox power station |name = Kahl Nuclear Power Plant |image = VAK_Kahl.jpg |image_size = |image_caption = VAK Kahl |image_alt = |location_map = Germany |location_map_size = |location_map_caption = | coordinates = {{coord|50|3|32.83|N|8|59|14.2|E|region:DE_type:landmark|display=inline,title}} |coordinates_ref = |owner = |operator = VAK Kahl |construction_began = 1958 |commissioned = July 17, 1961 |decommissioned = November 25, 1985 |ps_units_decommissioned = 1 x 16 MW |ps_annual_generation = 83 GWh (in 1985) |website = }} The '''Kahl''' plant was the first [[nuclear power]] plant ever to be built in Germany. It was located in [[Karlstein am Main]] and was an (at the time) experimental [[boiling water reactor]]. It was built by [[General Electric]] and supplied by [[Siemens]]. At the end of 2008, the demolition works had been finished.
The station was the subject of the 1961 short documentary film, ''[[Kahl (film)|Kahl]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.german-films.de/filmarchive/browse-archive/view/detail/mode/oscar_doc/film/kahl/|title=KAHL|work=German Films Service|accessdate=17 January 2014}}</ref>
